commit_message:
Removing all code from previous dashboard incarnation

Clearing out all of the old code from the Sahara
dashboard repo in preparation for bringing the new
code back into the repo for the Mitaka release.

commit_message:
Rename folder with CLI tests

Since there were added tests which check object creation,
environment deployment, folder name 'simple_read_only' became
incorrect.

Partially implements: blueprint cli-tests-coverage-improvement

commit_message:
Adds os-win dependency spec

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/add-os-win-library

Hyper-V is involved in many of OpenStack components (nova, neutron,
cinder, ceilometer, etc.) and will be involved with other components
in the future.

A common library can be created in order to reduce the code duplication
between all these components (utils classes, which interacts directly
with Hyper-V through WMI), making it easier to maintain, review and
propose new changes to current and future components.

Change-Id: I55a702557bbc827f01d45870f80de88fe07a9148
Implements: blueprint add-os-win-library

commit_message:
Updated Docker and k8s DIB elements

* Kubernetes element was updated to base on v1.0.6
* Docker now has its own repo and has different package name.
  Also it is now installed via downloadable script.
  TODO: Need somehow to fix docker version to 1.8.2

Change-Id: I230e9705cb850e9fb3772a67284561907d4be615
Implements: blueprint update-k8-to-v1-dib-elements
Co-Authored-By: Alexey Deryugin <aderyugin@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
The output don't match with example commands in enforcement.rst

In RST document congress/doc/source/enforcement.rst.

The example create base data rules in 'alice' policy,
but create regular rules in 'classification' policy,
that cause the output of following commands don't
match with the example. Modify 'classification' to 'alice'
so that making the example more easy to understand.

Change-Id: Ie5ce1aa5a274678538c06cc0c4f9c6ba6063f344
Closes-Bug: #1510527

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

You have a few open questions that need answering but you're definitely on the right track.  The -1 comes from the point that I think we need to consider IPv6 for GUAs and not ULAs, since the tenet is that we will not be using NAT66 for external access and v6 addresses have to be routeable if they are to have external access - which implies an address scope that is associated with an external network and can be drawn from if a network may be attached to that network via a router.  (Eventually it may need to extend to VPNs and multiple external networks, but I think it's a base requirement it at least works with one external network to begin with.)"}, {'account_id': 12912, 'date': '2014-11-26 16:48:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
[install] Liberty updates for ceilometer

Update ceilometer configuration for Liberty.

Changes and testing specific to distribution packages
primarily involve Ubuntu. Other distributions may require
additional patches.

Implements: bp installguide-liberty
Change-Id: Ie0c2449bad5c780b02b1d76f78665ae501668c20

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-21 21:38:10.000000000', 'message': 'Add STATUS_DISPLAY_CHOICE which matches Nova vm state

While working on another defect I noticed the value Horizon is using
in the status tuple for an instance which was soft deleted did not
match the string Nova is using for vm state.
Horizon is currently using the value "soft_deleted" in the
STATUS_DISPLAY_CHOICES tuple.  Nova is using the string
"soft-delete".  A more consistent approach in Nova would be to use
the string "soft_deleted" however changing this in Nova may
inadvertently change a REST API.
Adding a choice for "soft-delete" to Horizon enables Horizon to
translate the vm state correctly now.  Leaving the existing choice
of "soft_deleted" in Horizon ensures we will still work in the
future if Nova makes a change.

Change-Id: Icefd458bc3633c6fc8103e39966b9916722ff97f
Closes-Bug: #1506177
'}, {'created': '2015-10-22 12:15:56.000000000', 'message': 'Add STATUS_DISPLAY_CHOICE which matches Nova vm state

in the status tuple for an instance which was soft deleted did not
match the string Nova is using for vm state.
Horizon is currently using the value "soft_deleted" in the
STATUS_DISPLAY_CHOICES tuple.  Nova is using the string
"soft-delete".  A more consistent approach in Nova would be to use
the string "soft_deleted" however changing this in Nova may
inadvertently change a REST API.
Adding a choice for "soft-delete" to Horizon enables Horizon to
translate the vm state correctly now.  Leaving the existing choice
of "soft_deleted" in Horizon ensures we will still work in the
future if Nova makes a change.

commit_message:
Add STATUS_DISPLAY_CHOICE which matches Nova vm state

While working on another defect I noticed the value Horizon is using
in the status tuple for an instance which was soft deleted did not
match the string Nova is using for vm state.
Horizon is currently using the value "soft_deleted" in the
STATUS_DISPLAY_CHOICES tuple.  Nova is using the string
"soft-delete".  A more consistent approach in Nova would be to use
the string "soft_deleted" however changing this in Nova may
inadvertently change a REST API.
Adding a choice for "soft-delete" to Horizon enables Horizon to
translate the vm state correctly now.  Removing the existing choice
of "soft_deleted".

Change-Id: Icefd458bc3633c6fc8103e39966b9916722ff97f
Closes-Bug: #1506177

commit_message:
remove gratuitous python packages

With pip + upper-constraints we're nearly always over installing all
python packages because we no longer support a range, we support
*exactly* one version.

This removes a bunch of the gratuitous package installs which we're
going to install over, lxml, numpy, libvirt. All of these we had
coming from packages in the past for speed concerns, but upper
constraints removes that.

It also ensures that all the headers to build all those are in
general, so they are guarunteed available at all times.

Change-Id: Ia76de730d65c84d81c4fb2c980ae1b4d595f9f5b
(cherry picked from commit 5f8133caac097235ed4fe73d878df0ee907eb51c)

commit_message:
Log an error on an uncaught exception in a thread

Exceptions in synchronous tasks get caught by the olso_messaging code but
for asynchronous tasks run in threads with nothing wait()ing for them,
there is no top level error handling, and hence no logging. (Tracebacks
would be written to stderr, so systemd users would see them only in the
journal rather than heat-engine.log, and other users would quite likely
lose them altogether.) This change ensures that any uncaught exceptions are
logged as errors.

Change-Id: I9410aa7ffd83391ea4db13c6e8cf49f26d3049fb
Closes-Bug: #1492427

commit_message:
Move Key gen script to cmd folder

Moves the keygeneration script from bin to cmd folder.
This is preferred because other scripts for HSM interaction
such as the PKEK re-wrap are located here.

Change-Id: I731ec087e96114d00bd983edd60d2e1806399e16

commit_message:
Remove unused methods in client module

This patch proposes a removal of some methods that are never used in the
client module. They will eventually get invoked from sdk. We don't need
to do this at senlin client's side.

remove default=None for config options

In the cfg module default=None is set as the default value.

Change-Id: I3a60876dc90a15267c51c3a3f83428896dcddced
Closes-bug: #1323975

commit_message:
Cleanup datasource_config_model.py

API datasource_config_model.py is useless at all.
Clean it up from Congress code tree and remove
related d6Cage.createservice() logic, that casue
unnecessary publish/subscribe.

commit_message:
Fix builtins table in policy.rst

In RST doc congress/doc/source/policy.rst

The builtins table lack important method, like equal(x,y),
and the 'arithmetic' table contain two catalogs: arithmetic
and comparison, spliting it to separate tables looks like
make sense.

Change-Id: Ib49b0bb9500712bb12949ecaf76509eb31e121e5
Closes-Bug: #1510762

[{'created': '2015-10-29 09:37:34.000000000', 'message': "Abstract function should use NotImplementedError

Instead of using a internal exception type it's better to
use the preexisting exception from python built-ins that
was designed for this propose (see [1]).

[1]: https://docs.python.org/2/library/exceptions.html#exceptions.NotImplementedError

Change-Id: I8f41b2e4c66f52710b2e52fc50b70b3fbb5421aa
"}]
commit_message:
Abstract function should use NotImplementedError

Instead of using a internal exception type it's better to
use the preexisting exception from python built-ins that
was designed for this propose (see [1]).

[1]: https://docs.python.org/2/library/exceptions.html#exceptions.NotImplementedError

Change-Id: I8f41b2e4c66f52710b2e52fc50b70b3fbb5421aa

commit_message:
Add --enable|--disable options to region create and set

The region create and set command does not include --enable|--disable
options. This patch adds it.

Change-Id: Id86c620d33408860d99bcf9c00f737870092c0fc
Closes-Bug: #1507838

commit_message:
Enhance devstack to support heat datasource driver

This commit adds support to configure heat datasource driver as
part of devstack plugin if heat services are enabled.This commit
also adds cleanup functionality as part of plugin.sh

Change-Id: I320d1c1a27a1362bbd4700adacca9a331dd62f53
Patially-Implements: blueprint add-devstack-plugin

commit_message:
Catch exceptions for restore_prev_rsrc/prepare_for_replace

Catch exceptions when calling restore_prev_rsrc or
prepare_for_replace, to make sure the failure will be
recorded and the resource will put into FAILED state.

Change-Id: If65953d6b8cbdc135d898119c0f43a133f2e1892
Closes-Bug: #1512496

commit_message:
Swarm: Map master address to api_address based on TLS

api_address is a API address instead of master node's IP address.
This patch fix it by adding a new OutputMapping, it will help to handle
the mapping from master address to api_address.

Also test cases added.

Closes-Bug: #1514311
Change-Id: I47baf92dd466150adbd75746d0cb804d108f7d5f

[{'created': '2015-10-27 04:41:52.000000000', 'message': "Fix fedora-minimal kernel-install on older platforms

fedora-minimal fails to build on Ubuntu Trusty due do being unable to
find the initrd (see Id4c04d7ae20068643df34d2fa31068e8a917a52d).

This is a rather obscure problem that comes from the intersection of
several things.

The first thing to note is that the post-install scripts of the
kernel-core package use kernel-install [1].  For whatever reason, this
installs the kernel to /boot/MACHINE-ID/KERNEL-VERSION

MACHINE-ID comes from /etc/machine-id; a UUID that should have been
created by the systemd post-inst scripts with systemd-machine-id-setup
[2].

The chroot environment provided for root.d elements has no kernel
file-systems like /proc or /dev mounted.  This is where differences in
the base-system come into play -- on more recent systems that
implement getrandom() systemd does not need /dev/urandom to generate
the machine-id [3]; we get a value and /etc/machine-id is populated.

On older platforms (Trusty), systemd-machine-id-setup fails (unable to
access /dev/urandom) and we end up with a blank /etc/machine-id.  This
ends up making kernel-install (the script) fail during yum's
installation of kernel-core, which means the initrd is not installed
correctly.

We end up bailing out in fedora-minimal/install.d/99-ramdisk, where we
try to put the installed ramdisk in /boot for the later grub install
scripts to find.

The solution here is to mount the standard kernel file-systems within
the chroot before we try installing.

[1] http://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/kernel-install.html
[2] http://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd-machine-id-setup.html
[3] https://github.com/systemd/systemd/blob/master/src/basic/random-util.c

Change-Id: Ibcce35da928f64e6a719b070bcc833346ee7ee92

commit_message:
Fix fedora-minimal kernel-install on older platforms

fedora-minimal fails to build on Ubuntu Trusty due do being unable to
find the initrd (see Id4c04d7ae20068643df34d2fa31068e8a917a52d).

This is a rather obscure problem that comes from the intersection of
several things.

The first thing to note is that the post-install scripts of the
kernel-core package use kernel-install [1].  For whatever reason, this
installs the kernel to /boot/MACHINE-ID/KERNEL-VERSION

MACHINE-ID comes from /etc/machine-id; a UUID that should have been
created by the systemd post-inst scripts with systemd-machine-id-setup
[2].

The chroot environment provided for root.d elements has no kernel
file-systems like /proc or /dev mounted.  This is where differences in
the base-system come into play -- on more recent systems that
implement getrandom() systemd does not need /dev/urandom to generate
the machine-id [3]; we get a value and /etc/machine-id is populated.

On older platforms (Trusty), systemd-machine-id-setup fails (unable to
access /dev/urandom) and we end up with a blank /etc/machine-id.  This
ends up making kernel-install (the script) fail during yum's
installation of kernel-core, which means the initrd is not installed
correctly.

We end up bailing out in fedora-minimal/install.d/99-ramdisk, where we
try to put the installed ramdisk in /boot for the later grub install
scripts to find.

The solution here is to mount the standard kernel file-systems within
the chroot before we try installing.

[1] http://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/kernel-install.html
[2] http://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/systemd-machine-id-setup.html
[3] https://github.com/systemd/systemd/blob/master/src/basic/random-util.c

Change-Id: Ibcce35da928f64e6a719b070bcc833346ee7ee92

commit_message:
Added 'master_addresses' to Bay in API

A bay has an attribute 'node_addresses' that lists the IP addresses
of each minion node. As the support of HA mode was added, we need a
similar attribute, said 'master_addresses', that lists the IP
addresses of each master node.

Change-Id: I56313d273f4524095348f9cfd3bcb0f7b31054f6

metadata: Switch to OpenStack namespace and bump to Kilo

This patch fixes the puppet forge namespace, and bump min dependency to
Kilo https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Puppet/releases.

Change-Id: I92c33a7afe5cf730fd65ba6582b85e99f2855392

commit_message:
DiskFileNoSpace check during object delete

On a full disk, a call to delete an object will fail when it tries to
write tombstones. Handling DiskFileNoSpace exception raised by
swift.common.utils.

Change-Id: I8f0cfcc4159ee154fcd3e7ca90c422aa5aadf0b3
Signed-off-by: Ganesh Maharaj Mahalingam <ganesh.mahalingam@intel.com>
Closes-Bug: 1491675

[{'created': '2015-11-03 18:13:35.000000000', 'message': 'Add requestsexceptions to global requirements

Source:
https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/requestsexceptions

PyPI: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/requestsexceptions

Import exceptions from potentially bundled packages in requests.

The python requests library bundles the urllib3 library, however, some
software distributions modify requests to remove the bundled library.
This makes some operations, such as supressing the "insecure platform
warning" messages that urllib emits difficult. This is a simple library
to find the correct path to exceptions in the requests library regardless
of whether they are bundled.

Consuming projects
==================

This is used by shade.

This will be a proposed requirement of os-client-config.

Is the library actively maintained?
===================================

Yes, the library is actively maintained by the OpenStack Infra team.

The latest release was November 2015.

Is the library good code?
=========================

The actual library is very small, and although mostly undocumented, is
well structured and easy to follow:

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/requestsexceptions/tree/requestsexceptions/__init__.py

Is the library python 3 compatible?
===================================

Yes.

Is the library license compatible?
==================================

freezegun's LICENSE is Apache 2.0:

Is the library already packaged in the distros we target?
=========================================================

No, but there is no reason packaging it will be hard.

Is the function of this library already covered by other libraries?
===================================================================

Nope.

commit_message:
Add requestsexceptions to global requirements

Source:
https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/requestsexceptions

PyPI: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/requestsexceptions

Import exceptions from potentially bundled packages in requests.

The python requests library bundles the urllib3 library, however, some
software distributions modify requests to remove the bundled library.
This makes some operations, such as supressing the "insecure platform
warning" messages that urllib emits difficult. This is a simple library
to find the correct path to exceptions in the requests library regardless
of whether they are bundled.

Consuming projects
==================

This is used by shade.

This will be a proposed requirement of os-client-config.

Is the library actively maintained?
===================================

Yes, the library is actively maintained by the OpenStack Infra team.

The latest release was November 2015.

Is the library good code?
=========================

The actual library is very small, and although mostly undocumented, is
well structured and easy to follow:

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/requestsexceptions/tree/requestsexceptions/__init__.py

Is the library python 3 compatible?
===================================

Yes.

Is the library license compatible?
==================================

requestsexceptions's LICENSE is Apache 2.0:

Is the library already packaged in the distros we target?
=========================================================

No, but there is no reason packaging it will be hard.

Is the function of this library already covered by other libraries?
===================================================================

Nope.

Change-Id: I52249b6d2fe04c49a9f4ed139d7625c890309ca8

commit_message:
Remove unused has_admin_extensions()

has_admin_extensions() had not been used since the commit
Id36a6ebddb618a78cee7025c9537cd1e2746190e.
So it is nice to remove it for cleanup.

Change-Id: Ie828bb82da4a6453f8934a8a85a23944bc4f4eed

commit_message:
split out k8s and api functional testing

This patch splits out api and functional testing case to different directory,
and modify post_test_hook.sh to passing a parameter to calling different tox
venv.

commit_message:
Initial basic privsep functionality

Supports starting privileged process via fork or sudo, and a thread-safe
client and server communication mechanism.

Coming in later changes:
 - Extend json encoding to deal with non-unicode and more varied dict
   keys (see test_comm.py).
 - eventlet test case.
 - Linux capabilities.

Change-Id: If6456631c51d4f2a1c95805ab9d6962b04f172bc
Implements: blueprint privsep

commit_message:
iboot: add wait loop for pstate to activate

Add a short retry loop so that power state changes can
have some time to become active on iboot devices with
remote switches.

Closes bug: #1512478

Change-Id: Ifad4b6a22f0289b2bcec25528566326a2688e76b

This suggestion is certainly not for the L-release, but I think we should rethink this configuration stuff and make it behave more naturally.

We could have the common (default) option group + datastore-specific groups. Sort of what we have now, except we would programatially build and register the groups (each registered group would be a combination of the datastore-specific + all common option not overridden in the specific group).
That way could have stuff like this defined in the common, plus any overrides or additional options defined in the specific groups.
The datastore-specific groups would shrink to just the extra/overrides stuff.
Because each registered group would then contain all options, retrieving a value would simplify to a single 'get' - no more gymnastics with exceptions...

All that logic could be confined in the cfg module, updating the existing code should therefore be relatively easy."}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2015-09-24 15:03:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Workflow-1

very good catch y'all. Let me think about this some more. commit_message:
Move ignore_dbs and ignore_users out of DEFAULT

ignore_dbs and ignore_users (for MySQL) were still in DEFAULT section
of config. Moved them to the 'mysql' section and 'percona'
section. Sample config file(s) have been updated as well.

Change-Id: I3a41bcb011a76343afa3bcc30013cb835e456950
Closes-Bug: #1465242
Closes-Bug: #1480448
Closes-Bug: #1480447
Closes-Bug: #1374004

commit_message:
Move supported messaging drivers in-tree

Up until now it has only been available in the OpenStack spec, but it is
a living document and I believe we can maintain it in oslo.messaging's
tree.

Change-Id: I7bb9e5f02004f857d8f75909fcc0d05f2882a77d

commit_message:
Ensure__repr__ return value is encoded

When __repr__ returns an unicode object, python will
try to encode it with the default encoding scheme
which is ascii in general. So __repr__ needs to make
sure its return value is properly encoded.

Change-Id: Ifdb8c073474a917207a48fc5af5a340e87f66fc4
Closes-Bug: #1514325

sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.

commit_message:
Try to use zuul-cloner to prepare fixtures

In OpenStack Infra, we would like to run Puppet unit tests that
sometimes depends on other Puppet OpenStack modules.
Example: a patch in puppet-openstacklib that needs to be tested in puppet-nova.

This patch modifies the Rakefile to:
* clean spec_prep and spec_clean Rake tasks
* use openstack/puppet-openstack-integration/install_modules_unit.sh script
  to clone modules.
* do not use .fixtures.yaml file to clone modules and rely on
  zuul-cloner or git.
* Add openstack/ in gitignore so we never commit the
  puppet-openstack-integration repository (can happen when spec_clean
  did not run but you want to submit the patch anyway)
* Allow to run a custom Puppetfile if PUPPETFILE env is exported. It
  will allow people to test the module with the dependencies they like,
  feature we had with .fixtures.yaml.

Also add 'r10k' to Gemfile.

That way, we will be able to use zuul dependencies and run tests accross
modules like we do with functional testing.

Patch with original change-id I7b5af3ea6b21009a505a8b6c49086d339eaa43e5
for stable/kilo was merged without resolved comments.

Change-Id: I7f4169fa88bb4d5622a3e35b3ae2ff8a6380a514

commit_message:
Really get the "general" packages

We are specifying the argument to get_packages incorrectly, so we are
not actually adding the packages in "general" to the list of packages.

In most cases, this is hidden as other more specific plugins/services
request their packages.  However, as
I2dafd32f211fcbc9fff53030d736d97a5f1bb2df shows, not always.  I think
this was uncovered by 5f8133caac097235ed4fe73d878df0ee907eb51c

Change-Id: Ie1b8d09369281059d21da61b2725a457f708ae9e

commit_message:
Unify common output keys across Heat templates

After this commit, all Heat templates have five common outputs:
* api_address: API endpoint of specific COE.
* kube_masters/swarm_master/mesos_master: Public IP address(es) of
  master node(s).
* kube_masters_private/swarm_master_private/mesos_master_private:
  Private IP address(es) of master node(s).
* kube_minions/swarm_nodes/mesos_slaves: List of public IP addresses
  of worker nodes.
* kube_minions_private/swarm_nodes_private/mesos_slaves_private:
  List of private IP addresses of worker nodes.

Change-Id: Ie44136dafa326db598a5f17978d89adce8e69801
Closes-Bug: #1514252

[{'created': '2015-10-20 22:47:44.000000000', 'message': 'Fix attibute error when cloning raw images in Ceph

A regression introduced in If03b166d3ecc3e7fa6b7f1a0c69f8ab1cc7b1972
causes a ceph volume with the type raw fail to CoW or launch at all
in this case.

Change-Id: I7ae107bfccab7ff66c09d96856722dd6e60fdd96
Closes-Bug: #1508230
'}, {'created': '2015-11-09 08:36:09.000000000', 'message': "Fix attibute error when cloning raw images in Ceph

A regression introduced in If03b166d3ecc3e7fa6b7f1a0c69f8ab1cc7b1972
causes a glance image with the type 'raw' in ceph to fail to CoW
clone which prevents launching at all in this case.

The original patch did not update imagebackend.py [1] to use the new
nova.objects.ImageMeta object so the clone() function passes a normal
dict to the is_cloneable() function.

Additionally add another test to ensure that not passing disk_format
will fail, but not result in an exception. It will simply mean that
the function returns that it cannot take advantage of the CoW cloning
ceph provides.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/f2e2a5891d5f5ff9346e6dc8e4dd0e994485245c/nova/virt/libvirt/imagebackend.py#L824

commit_message:
Fix attibute error when cloning raw images in Ceph

A regression introduced in If03b166d3ecc3e7fa6b7f1a0c69f8ab1cc7b1972
causes a glance image with the type 'raw' in ceph to fail to CoW
clone which prevents launching at all in this case.

The original patch did not update imagebackend.py [1] to use the new
nova.objects.ImageMeta object so the clone() function passes a normal
dict to the is_cloneable() function.

Additionally add another test to ensure that not passing disk_format
will fail, but not result in an exception. It will simply mean that
the function returns that it cannot take advantage of the CoW cloning
ceph provides.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/f2e2a5891d5f5ff9346e6dc8e4dd0e994485245c/nova/virt/libvirt/imagebackend.py#L824

Change-Id: I7ae107bfccab7ff66c09d96856722dd6e60fdd96
Closes-Bug: #1508230
(cherry picked from commit 835ff1bf73d36a311168283f8a4ef5bec03d5a7e)

commit_message:
Use oslo.middleware SSLMiddleware

This change replaces Heat homemade SSLMiddleware by oslo.middleware
one. SSLMiddleware now should be defined in oslo_middleware section
instead of DEFAULT one (which is deprecated).

DocImpact

Related-Bug: #1444490
Change-Id: Ic8ef2c1c5ccbd64cf4c1a2845e2dd5914b88c2da

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-23 06:46:27.000000000', 'message': "Fix Kuryr not to create the duplicated port on creatign an endpoint

This patch fixes Kuryr to examine if a port with the same name exist
before creating it and create a new one only when it doesn't exist yet.

With --cluster-store for the Docker daemon, the API call against a
remote driver on a host is propergated to other remote drivers. In this
situation if /NetworkDriver.CreateEndpoint is called, Kuryr tries to
create the duplicated port on different hosts and got the
MacAddressInUseClient exception from the Neutron client like one below.

MacAddressInUseClient: Unable to complete operation for network
0802076e-6a5a-4add-aa51-10a90d909e9d. The mac address fa:16:3e:eb:6e:13
is in use.

Change-Id: I1f805cf7e7f1312997be1b190caffa2f8634b31b
Signed-off-by: Taku Fukushima <f.tac.mac@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1509197
"}]
commit_message:
Fix Kuryr not to create the duplicated port on creatign an endpoint

This patch fixes Kuryr to examine if a port with the same name exist
before creating it and create a new one only when it doesn't exist yet.

With --cluster-store for the Docker daemon, the API call against a
remote driver on a host is propergated to other remote drivers. In this
situation if /NetworkDriver.CreateEndpoint is called, Kuryr tries to
create the duplicated port on different hosts and got the
MacAddressInUseClient exception from the Neutron client like one below.

MacAddressInUseClient: Unable to complete operation for network
0802076e-6a5a-4add-aa51-10a90d909e9d. The mac address fa:16:3e:eb:6e:13
is in use.

Change-Id: I1f805cf7e7f1312997be1b190caffa2f8634b31b
Signed-off-by: Taku Fukushima <f.tac.mac@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1509197

commit_message:
Move install of simport to virtualenv setup

Move the simport install to the virtaulenv setup
section so that individual components do have
to have the extra parameters in their install
commands.

commit_message:
Enable network services at Kub master

It's common practice
(https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/tree/master/cluster) to run
network services (kube-proxy and flannel) at master. E.g. you can use
NodePort
(http://kubernetes.io/v1.0/docs/user-guide/services.html#type-nodeport)
for opening services to outside cluster. Flannel will be used later for
Kub services containerization (e.g.
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/240818)

Change-Id: I25b5f3c5931dab5d410702ab3737eea2f207ec35

Salvatore, thanks a lot for the comments. I'm sorry that I had not explained the problem clearly. Let me try to explain it at here:
1). How will the port switch-over case happen?
     There are two possibilities with the HVM instance depending on whether there is PV driver running with the instance: the port tapx.0 is active and vifx.0 is inactive if no PV driver running; otherwise tapx.0 is inactive and vifx.0 is active. But PV driver need some time to be loaded after instance boot up; so for the HVM instance which has PV driver, it will has PORT switch over case: Firstly tapx.0 is active; After PV driver is loaded successfully, the tapx.0 port turn to inactive and vifx.0 turns to be active. 

2). What's the problem if we only configure the active port but ignore the active one?
     In neutron, it won't detect the port change until it tries to poll the port status. So if we only configure the active port, it will have race condition: Depending on the polling interval, it may leave the active port not being configured. Image that the connect works firstly with that tapx.0 port and then it will lost network connect for a while before the port of vifx.0 is detected by neutron to be active.

3). What's the problem to create separate port objectives for inactive and active ports?
     Both the inactive and active ports service for the the same VIF inside the VM. So they have the same network properties. e.g. network id; iface-id .... And it uses the iface-id as the port's identification. So it's not easy to create two objectives. And I'm not sure but doubt it may introduce new issues at somewhere else due to it has multiple port entries for the same instance VIF. With the implement in this patch set, it restricts the inactive port at the layer of this VIF PORT class but only expose the active port to the higher layers. 

      Please feel free to let me know if any further clarification is needed and any comments are highly appreciated."}, {'account_id': 17920, 'date': '2015-10-28 16:20:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(4 comments)'}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2015-11-09 14:47:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

This change should be abandoned in favor of Change-Id: I0cfc0284e1fcd1a6169d31a7ad410716037e5cc2'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-11-09 19:35:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 17920, 'date': '2015-11-10 01:58:20.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

After some discussion, it's not a good solution by tracking two ports in neutron. it's thought that may break the neutron design. So we will go with the solution with change in nova to add a interim bridge between VM and the integration bridge. So in the world of neutron, it need only monitor the patch port connecting the interim bridge to the integration bridge. In this way, the switch over case between active and inactive port is transparent to neutron. 
  So this patch set will be abandoned and the new solution will be covered by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/242846/
  Thanks all."}]

commit_message:
ovs: ovs agent updates the wrong port when using Xen + Neutron

Note:
 This patch set is still WIP; Need to cover UT code and refine code.
 Any comments for the design or else are welcome and appreciated.

Problem description:
When VM is under HVM mode, ovs will create two ports and two interfaces for
a single virtual ethernet interface inside the VM: One is named as tapx.0
which is qemu-emulated NIC, used when no PV drivers installed; The other
one is named as vifx.0 which is the xen network frontend NIC, used when
VM has PV drivers installed. Depending on the PV driver's existing,
either of the two ports/interfaces will be used. But current implement
can NOT process multiple ports/interfaces. If it configures(e.g. set tag)
one interface but the other one is in fact used by ovs; it will have
network problem.

Solution:
When there are two ports/interfaces, one is active and the other is
inactive. Follow the existing working for the active one; but also
add fields to holde the inactive one. And try to apply same conf to
both ports.

Change-Id: Ic00d2cd83ef4104388df42c97118b02be30b22be
Closes-Bug: #1268955

commit_message:
Continuous systems management in Security Guide

In References section
The "OpenStack Security Primer" has a link where the music
piracy blog doesn't exist. The owner took it down. So this fix
is to remove the reference to it.

Change-Id: I206c249af1bc27732dd07489ccb8d687fe3343b7
Closes-bug: #1510806

I'll re-add it. Thanks"}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-09-22 17:26:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

having sat down and look through the code, I have some issues with the approach we have taken here.

Nested quotas seem to be behaving differently to regular quotas.

Generally we allow people to hand out too much quota, if thats what they want to do. I think we should allow the same thing with nested quotas.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-09-22 17:38:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I am also curious how this related to Cinder:
http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/cinder-specs/specs/liberty/cinder-nested-quota-driver.html

We should mention this in the spec now, ideally.'}, {'account_id': 136, 'date': '2015-09-22 17:57:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I would be very keen to maintain identical semantics between cinder and nova for nested quota (along with subsequent projects). The teams have been in regular contact and https://blueprints.launchpad.net/cinder/+spec/cinder-nested-quota-driver included in the cinder liberty deliverables.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-09-25 17:56:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

totally agreed we need compatible semantics between the two, i.e. you must be able to do with nova what you can do with cinder'}, {'account_id': 8866, 'date': '2015-10-01 13:05:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-01 13:12:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

- gate-nova-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/69/209969/3/check/gate-nova-specs-python27/f3c4be6/ : SUCCESS in 2m 08s'}, {'account_id': 11057, 'date': '2015-10-01 14:07:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi John,
       1. Raildo has added link to the cinder bp. Actually this bp was made during Juno cycle , while cinder bp was not there.That was why that link was missing.

       2. Functionalities of nova and cinder will be same.

       3. In your comments , you had mentioned about iteratively going up to the root project , which has no parent, for the purpose of giving more quota.
         While we were designing this bp one year back , we had thought about that.
        But we had abandoned that idea thinking that users would not be comfortable in an iterative approach, as the quota may propagate from leaf project to the root project.
 
        So we had thought keeping the design simpler , by confining the operation among parent and its immediate children.
        So IMHO in the the first release , we can restrict the operation among parent and its immediate children.
        Later , we can go for the iterative one, after getting feedback from the users.'}, {'account_id': 8866, 'date': '2015-10-01 14:23:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 11057, 'date': '2015-10-01 14:24:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

John: In the current quota code , I have allowed excess quota only for the root project , to avoid the need for iterative quota allocation up to the root project. 

Kindly give your feedback.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-01 14:38:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

@sajeesh, do ping me on IRC (johnthetubaguy) if I am unresponsive in gerrit, its easy for me to miss review comments in my email soup.

To your previous comment, I think we should the sum of quota given to all sub tenants to exceed that of their parent, because its an important part of'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-10-07 10:21:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

oh dear, I hadn't finished that comment, sorry.

I think its important to allow sub tenants to have their quota add up more than the parent tenant, because it matches how you can hand out more quota to users in your cloud, than the cloud has quota.

I am worried people we try to use this for "dedicated" resources, but this is not actually going to work, most of the time, because the original quota is not dedicated in any way.

I get users might want to share out their full capacity quota strictly between groups, than then delegate it, but when we add this support, we should really support the general use case here.

Now there is another issue here. Our current quota system is very complex and buggy. we have a possibly solution written up but no one to work on it. And this builds on the current buggy quota system, and adds more complexity, making quotas harder to fix in the long run. We need to work out what is going on there.'}, {'account_id': 7953, 'date': '2015-10-08 13:20:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hi, John,

we'd like to discuss the use cases for overcommitting quota and the consequences it would have in the hierarchical project scenario in our meeting slot on Friday as well as options to support this or not. It would be great to have you involved in this discussion. Would you be available (16:00 UTC 18:00 MEST) ?"}, {'account_id': 11057, 'date': '2015-10-08 17:52:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@john ... I agree with you .
Overcommit is an useful feature, that should be made available to all projects , and not just root projects.

But there will be some consequences. An over 

commit on a leaf project will propagate up to the root

project thereby  affecting the complete tree. 

As Ulrich had suggested , can you please join us in

tomorrow's meeting."}, {'account_id': 136, 'date': '2015-10-08 18:20:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I feel it is really important to get consistent semantics with the cinder driver. Users will find it confusing if we are inconsistent and this will propagate to future projects with quotas such as Neutron and Magnum.'}, {'account_id': 11057, 'date': '2015-10-09 15:22:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Code-Review

@Tim we have two main objectives.

1. NestedQuotaDriver should preserve all the features of DbQuotaDriver.

2. NestedQuotaDriver in Nova should have the same semantics as that of CinderQuotaDriver. 

In any case, if these objectives are conflicting the former(1) should have the preference (IMHO).

I have to check how cinder has handled over commit.

@Vilobh, Erickson can you please comment on this.'}, {'account_id': 15359, 'date': '2015-10-09 15:36:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I agree with Tim Bell. It should be really good if we keep the consistency between Cinder and Nova drivers.

@Sajeesh In the current implementation of nested quotas in cinder we are not allowing overcommit. If Nova is moving towards this direction, I believe it's worth thinking in a way to preserve the consistency between the services."}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-10-09 17:42:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Sajeesh : As Eric mentioned in Cinder we don't have support for Overcommit in place as of now. The approach taken for cinder was :-

#Phase 1 : Have basic model for Nested Quota in Liberty which works as per spec  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/173141/

#Phase 2 : Add support for concurrent request. This was discussed at the design summit may be at this point would think about adding overcommit related cases as well.

IMHO having a basic infrastructure in place and building on top of it is the way we went for in Cinder. 

Considering this as a big feature going one step at a time can help. We consider overcommit related cases as a useful addition and will consider doing it in upcoming release."}, {'account_id': 11057, 'date': '2015-10-09 17:55:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Vilobh , Erickson thanks a lot for the clarifications.

@Erickson I totally agree with you and Tim , that consistency between different services is important.

What I meant was that , preserving the existing(useful) features of the previous driver inside a single service is far more important.'}, {'account_id': 8866, 'date': '2015-10-13 12:34:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-13 16:10:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

Moving Nested Quota Driver to Mitaka

Nested quota driver will enable OpenStack to enforce quota in nested
projects.

Previously-approved: Liberty

commit_message:
New local certificate generator uses local time

The new local certificate generator code uses local time
for validity periods causing failures on hosts that do not
use UTC time.
This patch changes this to always use UTC time for certificate
generation.

Change-Id: Ice15ab53f322ac148c85e1f6e781f63f661d6179
Closes-Bug: #1514601

[{'created': '2015-10-06 03:02:53.000000000', 'message': 'dib-lint: ignore blank lines in element ordering

Some of the elements-deps in the project-config repo have a blank line
at the end, which throws out the ordering.  Strip blank lines, like
comment lines, before processing.

commit_message:
dib-lint: ignore blank lines in element ordering

Some of the elements-deps in the project-config repo have a blank line
at the end, which throws out the ordering.  Strip blank lines, like
comment lines, before processing.

As an additional help, show a side-by-side diff of what is provided
versus what is expected when showing an error about sorting.

Change-Id: I007851ee01d6853ad992ce4437331e8bd79bbfce

commit_message:
Pull the endpoint from the Session

If the user passes a Session in, we can pull the endpoint to use for
discovery from the Session itself, rather than erroring.

Closes-Bug: #1513839
Co-Authored-By: Dolph Mathews <dolph.mathews@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I82a41c67f80d2494f04739d82b112b7ff1dc4682

commit_message:
Initial checkin

This adds most of the files from app-catalog-ui into this common
location so it can be shared soon with app-catalog-ui and
apps.openstack.org. Its currently only usable by apps.openstack.org
and will need further work to be shared. But its a start.

Change-Id: I63bff3be6180ff12ab0055c15ff04fd4a7631684

Changes include:
- storage nodes reporting when they have >1 fragment archive
available
- GET path recognizing alternates, when to use them and building
up the getters accordingly leveraging existing greenpool
- associated test changes for existing code
- new unit tests and new probe tests

commit_message:
EC GET path: support use of alternate fragments on object servers

Changes include:
- storage nodes reporting when they have >1 fragment archive
available
- GET path recognizing alternates, when to use them and building
up the getters accordingly leveraging existing greenpool
- HEAD reports available alt frags
- associated test changes for existing code
- new unit tests and new probe tests

Note:  non-EC policies ignore alt-frag headers

Co-Authored-By: Alistair Coles <alistair.coles@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Minwoo Bae <minwoob@us.ibm.com>
Change-Id: Id21853498af9f424fe5f5cf7f37017e89a4d67b9
Closes-Bug: 1484598

commit_message:
Parse Sample volume as float

Explicitly parses sample volume as float to
prevent incorrect sample from being published.
In case of an sample with wrong volume type or
no volume. the sample is dropped and a warning
is logged.

Change-Id: Ia81d309876ba4a358d8d8187e11a08867fb0b267
Closes-Bug: #1508220

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
remove py26 and py33 test

OpenStack has dropped the support for old python version 2.6, we can follow
it to reduce our maintain burden and save CI resources.
And we already have py34 test, which is enabled on Gerrit by default,
py33 test is not necessary now.

Change-Id: Ie2904d040ab86817c852b2f39b542814441e4dc3
Closes-Bug: #1500239

commit_message:
Move policy update logic to cluster

This patch makes update_policy a method of the cluster class. The intent
is to make it reusable outside an action context. Update policy is
useful when, for example, temporarily disable a policy on a cluster.

Change-Id: I6417539792dfb1485ac93492cb4bf858b676bc7f

commit_message:
Update TODO/FEATURE item list

This patch updates TODO.rst and FEATURE.rst based on the
discussion in Tokyo meetup. The backlogs of Liberty cycle are
picked up and some TODO items which are in long-term plan are
moved from TODO.rst to FEATURES.rst.

Change-Id: I799deb7adb3abbe066ac92f0f2cdbd0acc4265d3

[{'created': '2015-04-16 15:45:38.000000000', 'message': 'Agent Group and Tooz Driver

Proper operations in Neutron depends on agent monitoring information
and health status. Currently there is a heartbeat/DB based mechanism.
It is not instant, extremely inefficient and not scalable.

A much more lightweight, scalable and reliable agent status monitoring
and querying mechanism is desired for neutron. We would like to introduce
AgentGroup to neutron, which provides internal API for neutron agent
grouping, membership registration, health status check, group member
querying, etc. Modules such as failure detective, scheduler and HA will
use AgentGroup and its API.

There are many different backend which can be used to implement those
functionalities in AgentGroup. Instead of having neutron to maintain,
test, upgrade those code, we intend to introduce a tooz driver, and use
tooz library to manage/maintain 3rd party backend such as zookeeper, redis,
etc. Also, considering backward compatibility with original DB-based
mechanism, since it uses tables and data model that is intrinsically tied
to the internal of neutron, tooz cannot take it over. So a DB-based driver
is needed for AgentGroup, just the same as how nova ServiceGroup refactoring
spec solves the compatibility issue.

Change-Id: I1cdb832abc9c42a218cfb975c946eac87108d8da
Blueprint: agent-group-and-tooz-driver
'}]
commit_message:
Agent Group and Tooz Driver

Proper operations in Neutron depends on agent monitoring information
and health status. Currently there is a heartbeat/DB based mechanism.
It is not instant, extremely inefficient and not scalable.

A much more lightweight, scalable and reliable agent status monitoring
and querying mechanism is desired for neutron. We would like to introduce
AgentGroup to neutron, which provides internal API for neutron agent
grouping, membership registration, health status check, group member
querying, etc. Modules such as failure detective, scheduler and HA will
use AgentGroup and its API.

There are many different backend which can be used to implement those
functionalities in AgentGroup. Instead of having neutron to maintain,
test, upgrade those code, we intend to introduce a tooz driver, and use
tooz library to manage/maintain 3rd party backend such as zookeeper, redis,
etc. Also, considering backward compatibility with original DB-based
mechanism, since it uses tables and data model that is intrinsically tied
to the internal of neutron, tooz cannot take it over. So a DB-based driver
is needed for AgentGroup, just the same as how nova ServiceGroup refactoring
spec solves the compatibility issue.

Change-Id: I1cdb832abc9c42a218cfb975c946eac87108d8da
Blueprint: agent-group-and-tooz-driver

[{'account_id': 1528, 'date': '2015-09-24 02:01:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-24 03:02:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-pycadf-python26 http://logs.openstack.org/82/227082/1/check/gate-pycadf-python26/45e56b6/ : SUCCESS in 54s

- gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-src-pycadf http://logs.openstack.org/82/227082/1/check/gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-src-pycadf/47e49a9/ : SUCCESS in 57m 30s'}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2015-09-24 06:52:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

So, the way i'm reading the spec (https://www.dmtf.org/sites/default/files/standards/documents/DSP2038_1.1.0.pdf) i don't think "name" is necessary.

The event itself already contains a lot of to uniquely identify the event, so i'm not sure why a 'name' would be helpful.

With that said, pyCADF events are designed to be extendible, so you can add fields to the event that is generated. You just have to do:

  setattr(event, key, value)'}, {'account_id': 7514, 'date': '2015-09-24 14:48:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Steve's assessment of the spec. is correct as the event itself (via the normative taxonomies) within the typURI for the resources that participate in the event along with the action and outcome values (which are also from normative taxonomies). In addition, for OpenStack, we record and extra attribute "request path" (e.g., "'requestPath': '/v2/56600971-90f3-4370-807f-ab79339381a9/servers',") which captures the OpenStack API path used that generated the event. If you need to map the event back to another domain (e.g., a non-OpenStack API or an event coming from a controller or plug-on below the API within some service) then as Steve pointed out one can add an additional attribute.  The processors of CADF must, by spec., preserve these extra events but typically can ignore them for processing if they are not part of the domain that added them.'}, {'account_id': 7514, 'date': '2015-09-24 14:51:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

Stanislaw, what is the use case (or consumer of the event) where you believe a "name" field is needed?  Perhaps we can make a better recommendation of how to advise your use case be addressed.'}, {'account_id': 1528, 'date': '2015-09-25 00:18:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I submitted this based on http://www.dmtf.org/sites/default/files/standards/documents/DSP0262_1.0.0.pdf which includes name in the event.

My use case is related to https://review.openstack.org/#/c/227108/3/anchor/audit/__init__.py line 81. In Anchor I want to create an event for certificate signing. The problem I ran into is that there's no action/target combo that represents signing exactly. The best I found is "evaluate" on "data/security/key" with observer being "security/policy". I think it could work with an extra description which is "certificate signing".

I'm happy to do it in some other way if you can suggest better solutions.'}, {'account_id': 7514, 'date': '2015-09-28 13:54:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Indeed, the spec. allows for name as an optional field with the description: 

"This optional property represents a descriptive name for 
the event.
This property SHALL NOT be used in place of 
the required CADF Event property “id”.

We are really trying to discourage its usage as it is has no meaning in terms of the event model.  In addition, since it is optional, it would not be used for any analytics. If you are trying to create new domain-specific views a "tag" is the way to go.  However, you are correct that the "name" field should be accepted.'}, {'account_id': 6460, 'date': '2015-10-10 13:21:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

So I believe my understanding is the following.  Stanislaw is implementing an optional feature clearly defined in the spec.  At the same time we believe his use case should not be using this field. So if he came to us and said I want to add this so I can add a descriptive name (as is the spec reasoning for having this optional field) my guess is we would have accepted the code.  It really comes down to how strongly you want to discourage this option. If you can think that there is at least one valid use case in the world for this field then I am a plus one.  If we have decided this field does nothing but causes harm then it should never go in.  Does my logic sound correct?'}, {'account_id': 7514, 'date': '2015-10-12 13:21:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Brad, you are correct.  Support for "name" is in the spec., so in that regard the field should be supported.  The more I consider this issue, it seems that if Stanislov wants to use it he of course may, but if he wants the additional data he is placing in that field to be meaningful beyond his domain, perhaps "tag" would be better since you can embed a "domain" into the URI or even use the "attachment" where again he can add an attachment "type" (which again provides an indicator of what data is being added).'}, {'account_id': 7514, 'date': '2015-10-12 13:21:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1528, 'date': '2015-10-13 02:27:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I think I got convinced not to use it in the way I planned. The patch still is technically correct, so I'm leaving it here, but if you decide not to merge it, I won't be sad :)"}, {'account_id': 6460, 'date': '2015-11-06 00:20:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

[{'created': '2015-05-19 09:43:19.000000000', 'message': 'Refactoring of L3 Scheduler

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/dhcpservice-loadbalancing

In the above mentioned blueprint, WeightScheduler has been introduced which
is used to effectively distribute the DHCP namespaces by checking the load on
each dhcp agent. DHCP agent load is calculated based on report status messages
received from them. The “dhcp service loadbalancing” blueprint had also
implemented BaseScheduler and BaseResourceFilter class hierarchy which should
be common for both dhcp_agent_scheduler and l3_agent_scheduler, however as of
now only dhcp_agent_scheduler is derived from BaseScheduler and updates the
load column of agents table.

This blueprint proposes refactoring of existing L3 Scheduler code to align
with the new design as implemented for dhcp Scheduler.

Change-Id: I89129c507d6b55b3c1546b522800661c22222a03
Co-Authored-By: Shivakumar M <shiva.kum.m@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Praveen Kumar SM <praveen-sm.kumar@hp.com>

commit_message:
Refactoring of L3 Scheduler

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/dhcpservice-loadbalancing

In the above mentioned blueprint, WeightScheduler has been introduced which
is used to effectively distribute the DHCP namespaces by checking the load on
each dhcp agent. DHCP agent load is calculated based on report status messages
received from them. The “dhcp service loadbalancing” blueprint had also
implemented BaseScheduler and BaseResourceFilter class hierarchy which should
be common for both dhcp_agent_scheduler and l3_agent_scheduler, however as of
now only dhcp_agent_scheduler is derived from BaseScheduler and updates the
load column of agents table.

This blueprint proposes refactoring of existing L3 Scheduler code to align
with the new design as implemented for dhcp Scheduler.

Co-Authored-By: Shivakumar M <shiva.kum.m@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Praveen Kumar SM <praveen-sm.kumar@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Aman Kumar <aman.kumar3@hpe.com>

Related-bug: #1509046

Change-Id: I89129c507d6b55b3c1546b522800661c22222a03

commit_message:
PBR version needs to be explicitly set on setup.py

For some reason PBR does not install dependencies if
the PBR version is not set in setup.py

Change-Id: I1edbe46a88b0592b34fe49e38fcdd8a6c85bfd4d

commit_message:
Traffic direction for FWaaS

Specification for adding traffic direction (ingress/egress/birectional) for firewall policy rules in FWaaS.

Co-Authored-By: Vikram Choudhary <vikram.choudhary@huawei.com>

Change-Id: I6f4bfe585211da4bd24643778eb7150099319d05
Implements: blueprint fwaas-rules-directions

commit_message:
Agent DB Refactor

For variant neutron agents, they share the same database model to store
basic information, configurations, as well as dynamic workload data.
Neutron-server depends on it to apply correct operations such as producing
API response, scheduling, and HA. Also, how to maintain, transport those
data is a performance factor to neutron. We believe the db model needs a
refactor, base on some thinkings of the two scenarios.

First, currently there is no attribute to identify agent logical status,
such as initializing, ready, data sync, or error. Once agent is connected
to neutron-server, only admin state and liveness is checked on server side.
That means neutron-server may apply operations on agent blindly.

Second, agents send heartbeat message to transport those data. However,
carrying/parsing static data and writing them to db everytime is
inefficient. We'd like to see static and dynamic data is well decoupled
in agent db model. Then agent only needs to send static data once, and
subsequent heartbeats only carry dynamic data.

Change-Id: Ib7d50aa71ed2c482030ea48cd2ed4434fa5744a9
Blueprint: agent-db-refactor

and health status. Currently there is a heartbeat/DB based mechanism.

commit_message:
Agent Group and Pluggable Status Drivers

Proper operations in Neutron depends on agent monitoring information
and health status. Currently there is a heartbeat/DB based mechanism.
It is not instant, extremely inefficient and not scalable. And there
is no open framework to integrate other backends/mechanism.

For a lightweight, scalable and reliable agent status monitoring
and querying mechanism, we would like to see a membership framework,
to aggregate variant agents by type, provide internal services such as
membership registration/health status check/group member querying, etc.
And, it should come with pluggable backend drivers, such as DB,
zookeeper, memcached.

Change-Id: If4e52ffc665b6ede896342951920e3425d1cd69a
Blueprint: agent-group-and-status-drivers

commit_message:
ML3 router: reference driver/agent for routervm

This blueprint proposes reference driver/agent for routervm.  Its goal
is consolidate independent L3-plugins for routervm by implementing
reference L3 router driver/agents.

Change-Id: I4017fde3f07abacd09f442148fdb9489e4023987
Blueprint: l3-plugin-for-routervm

(I can't open the example link you pasted in other comment, maybe a valid one belongs in the commit)

Another important thing is that you take care of cases where the ML2 mechanism driver doesnt use agents to implement security groups (There are already examples for this), just something to take into consideration

Another small point is that it seems from the text (to me) that you plan to combine security-groups, allowed address paris, security port into one extension, if thats the case its probably important to think if thats actually a good idea and think about backward compatibility (if that wasn't your plan, ignore my lack of understanding :) )"}, {'account_id': 9970, 'date': '2015-07-12 02:21:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Thanks @Gal, I will update it include the consideration the sec-group event for no agent design and your other advices.

My POC code is here: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/190891/

Actually, I want insert a new extension driver -- checker driver, to deal with the dependency with the sec-group,  address-pair, and the port-sec. But this driver will not exposed to users with configure file.

Thanks for Irena's advice -- integrated them all, but I think that will make users no choice, they only have all or nothing. And also use one ext driver to include 3 functions, maybe it's too heavy. I am not sure whether the three functions have been considered as whole function.

And Kolesnik, personally I agree that add a dependency chain will make the things worse. the system need deal with the loop and define the order delicately."}, {'account_id': 16707, 'date': '2015-07-31 07:02:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
ML2: convert security-group and address-pairs into extension driver

Create new extension drivers for security-group and extension driver, to
replace the legacy extension way. And refactor the process which verify the
potential conflict between drivers.

Change-Id: Ifa1212cb05654d613702fa0394a9fede92557fd8
Blueprint: ml2-extdriver-secgroup-addrpairs

The security group API is an API that has been brought over from Amazon. I don't know if it is wise to extend an API that has not really been designed in the OpenStack community, since Amazon could change their API at any point."}, {'account_id': 11343, 'date': '2015-05-22 12:44:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2015-06-09 18:32:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Sean, your point on Amazon compatibility makes somewhat sense.
On the other hand, we have use cases for expanding the concept of security groups.

If we "augment" security groups than we diverge from the amazon standard. But in my personal opinion when we started neutron we forked nova security groups which are in their turn a fork of EC2 security groups. So we already diverged (indeed do we have ingress and egress rules in EC2?).

also, there are many other reasons for which you would not be able to port an app written against EC2 to neutron, that make me believe EC2 and Neutron only share the concept of "security group" but not its implementation.

But let's assume we wont' touch security groups. Do you think we should have a new security API to address use cases like the one presented in this blueprint? And in that case would it be mutually exclusive with the security group API?'}, {'account_id': 7805, 'date': '2015-08-11 03:49:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

The API seems too complicated for Security Group Rule and not very clear for end-users to use. Is it possible to add a dedicated API for security enhancement (not to extend the current API)?'}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-08-17 18:32:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

What about using the QoS API that is in the process of being merged? That seems like a better option at this point'}, {'account_id': 13997, 'date': '2015-09-05 06:17:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
LBaaS: implements LVS driver

This commit adds an LVS loadbalancer driver using keepalived.
The loadbalancer is going to use LVS-DR forwarding.

Implements bp/lbaas-lvs-driver

commit_message:
Filter core resoruces based on extended attributes.

https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1405057

Currently we can't filter core neutron resources(Network, Subnet, Port) based
on extended attributes.

Adding a generic framework that will enable cloud user to filter resources
based on extendend attributes also.

Change-Id: I75e813ea2e1385d5da3d01cfee7175a3aaa44aae
Co-Authored-By: Shivakumar M <shiva.kum.m@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Saro Chandra Bhooshan <bhooshan@hp.com>

commit_message:
Enable setting default rules for default security group

In the current implementation, the default security group only contains the
rule that allow intercommunication between vms in a same security-group.
However, customers could be confused about that their vms can't use ssh or rdp
to login, or can't provide HTTP/HTTPS service to outside since the security
group is disabled to these ports by default.

To resolve this, we need to allow cloud administrators to set rules of default
security group.

Blueprint: default-rules-for-default-security-group

DocImpact

Change-Id: I2610b23c2bd6d2ba5ef9c4800b7e0615b47c46e6

commit_message:
Update requests_mock syntax

In most other libraries we use self.requests_mock as the mock object for
additional clarity. We can also use the HTTP method methods directly
rather than have to register_uri each time.

Change-Id: Ib30f85fab00bd488fc3ce2cffa04aa82e2fe4f34

[{'created': '2015-04-16 21:20:33.000000000', 'message': "Don't re-bind environment for get_file during stack update

While we're in the process of updating a stack, we set the stack's
environment to the new, updated values. However, we don't want to change
existing resources' idea of their own values until we have explivitly done
an update of them to bring them into line with the new
template/environment. So when parsing a template snippet containing the
get_file intrinsic, store the files dict to which it will refer. get_file

commit_message:
Don't re-bind environment for get_file during stack update

While we're in the process of updating a stack, we set the stack's
environment to the new, updated values. However, we don't want to change
existing resources' idea of their own values until we have explivitly done
an update of them to bring them into line with the new
template/environment. So when parsing a template snippet containing the
get_file intrinsic, store the files dict to which it will refer. get_file
will resolve to the new file only when the template has been updated.

Closes-Bug: #1445170
Change-Id: I8ec32b0e38389cd314e4b2b2d8c65f61f8a9c41e

commit_message:
Removes the use of mutables as default args

Passing mutable objects as default args is a known Python pitfall.
We'd better avoid this. This commit changes mutable default args with
None, then use 'arg = arg or {}', 'arg = arg or []'. For unit code which
doesn't use the args , just set with None. This commit also adds hacking
check.

Change-Id: Ib4f195c9c00ca2c49579f9d62648bff7c8109fcf
Closes-Bug: #1327473

commit_message:
fix ambiguous version number types

Some of the tooz versions can be parsed as floats, so the YAML parser is
doing that automatically. Wrap them in quotes to force them to be
treated as strings.

Change-Id: I422b3b79714c4d01c27c631af822d4e17144c17a

commit_message:
Add registry information to quickstart.rst

We get an awful lot of questions about how to operate with a registry
on the IRC channel and the obvious way to fix that is to document it.

I don't know what to document about Ubuntu but if someone leaves the
appropriate commands in the review I'll be happy to update it to include
the correct operations to make the registry run on Ubuntu.  Another option
is perhaps we can get Sam to write those docs once this hits the repo since
the structure will be mostly in place.

TrivialFix

commit_message:
Make Python implementations the default

Default the Monasca API and Monasca Persister to use
the Python implementations.

Change-Id: I890e82037efd5fc2f60e501cbde1935855efd66f

commit_message:
Add a Delete Modal Service for deleting entities

This provides a reusable modal service for deleting
entities. It can be used for deleting single or multiple
objects.

It requires that the backing API Service allow for
suppressing of errors so that success and error messages
are shown only once when working with multiple objects.

It's used in the patch
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/234873/

Change-Id: I9d6410c0d4a692db4044661254a9914eef79e3ed
Partially-Implements: blueprint ng-flavors

    c. template is the button's label if its an icon and some text or whatever else you want

commit_message:
Actions directive for dynamic actions

Actions are sensitive to user permissions
and are available based on context.
This directive allows for dynamically composing menu
actions based on how many actions are provided.

Co-Authored-By: Errol Pais<epais@thoughtworks.com>

Change-Id: I75f0e099a5dea723c4d8786ee810e8499db7305c
Partially-Implements: blueprint angularize-images-table

It's needed for psycopg2.

commit_message:
Add track_quota_usage conf into neutron.conf

track_quota_usage is missing in neutron configuration files. This
patch adds it into neutron.conf so that deployers know it.

Closes-bug: #1504370
DocImpact

Change-Id: Ibaff5ac60cd69958eb981d2058d946cc88f799f1

We need an owner for this.  @John, would you have any spare cycles to put up a patch to implement the API change?

As soon as a patch set is posted to make the API changes, this one can depend on it and I'll remove WIP."}, {'account_id': 4187, 'date': '2015-09-28 23:00:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

@Carl @John I have some cycles to devote to this if needed.'}, {'account_id': 6635, 'date': '2015-09-29 12:21:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

@Carl Yes I should have some time to work on this. Continuing the train of thought on the API changes, how about being able to set the default subnetpool on a per-tenant basis? That way the admin could very easily partition the subnet ranges for each of their tenants. I think we could do this by making two changes to the proposed plan:

1. Allow the "default" flag to be True for any number of subnetpools overall, but only for one subnetpool per tenant.

2. Achieve the above either implicitly based on the subnetpools that each tenant has access to, or explicitly by adding another column to the subnetpool table containing a list of the tenants for which that subnetpool is the default.

I believe both approaches in [2] would allow the creation of 'master' defaults that apply to all tenants, as well as individual per-tenant defaults (although not both at the same time). The second is more flexible however, and would be my preference.

@Carl @Ryan What do you think? This would also open the door for a prefix delegation enhancement I'd like to propose which would allow the admin to define different delegation pools for each tenant.'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-09-29 16:08:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I tend to think per-tenant defaults is getting a little ahead of ourselves until we have something rbac for pools working.

Currently the semantics for sharing pools with tenants is all or nothing.  So, if multiple pools have default set, all tenants will see multiple defaults unless the pools are not shared.  If they aren't shared, no one can see them."}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-09-29 16:13:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Just read the second part of your second bullet.  Even if we do down that road, please don't store a list of tenant ids in a new column on the subnet pool."}, {'account_id': 4187, 'date': '2015-09-29 19:41:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm with @Carl on the subjet of per-tenant defaults.  Per-tenant defaults will be a little too clunky right now. We've already rolled our own quota mechanism for subnetpools, no need to keep piling on more one-off solutions.  I also agree with the comment regarding adding a column to the subnetpools table."}, {'account_id': 6635, 'date': '2015-09-30 12:53:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ok, this is great. Looks like we've got plenty of consensus to begin the work. I've filed an RFE here https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1501328 and will get to work on a patch immediately."}, {'account_id': 6635, 'date': '2015-10-05 12:52:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I've posted a patch for the API changes here:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/230983/

It's WIP until Mitaka opens, but general feedback is always appreciated."}, {'account_id': 4187, 'date': '2015-10-16 16:54:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Could we include these changes in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/230983 and abandon this review? It might be nice to have a single commit that enables the cutover from neutron.conf options to an attribute on the subnetpool. I'm not adamant about this and could be persuaded either way though."}, {'account_id': 6635, 'date': '2015-10-16 16:56:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Ryan That would be fine with me, but I'll leave it to Carl to make the decision."}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-10-20 04:08:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Ryan, I'm fine with that.  @John, let me know when I can abandon this."}, {'account_id': 6635, 'date': '2015-10-20 11:27:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Carl Thanks, I've updated https://review.openstack.org/#/c/230983/ to remove the config options. You can abandon this patch now."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-05 19:39:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-11-09 21:35:29.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Deprecate default subnet pool options

These options have a number of issues:

1) Requires editing of config file after creating subnet pool through API [1][2].
2) API behavior depends on value of configuration which isn't visible through API [3].
   - Namely, to use the implicit pool will require an explicit None passed to the API.

Are there other issues?

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/207574
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/168098/5/etc/neutron.conf
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/199038/

This patch is a work in progress to discuss potential solutions to these issues.

Change-Id: I298baf71452b437792631129181c24459d5c2a59

commit_message:
Set nova ironic admin_url correctly

Update our nova.conf ironic config section so that we properly set
the admin_url. Previously it would always be localhost (which
isn't always what we bind to).

This patch also moves the nova::compute::ironic settings into
hiera.

Change-Id: Ic42f1af5b66acf187715599f72ddf983fefb33c7

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-09 19:46:23.000000000', 'message': "Add `@ngInject` to Job route resolve function

During production builds, the minifier modifies variable names,
breaking Angular's automatic dependency injection. The ng-annotate
declaration `@ngInject` was missing from the `resolve` config
for the Job route, causing all `/job/*` paths to become
inaccessible. This adds the correct annotation to solve the issue.

Change-Id: Ic5f68c6f3dfc840b563bde0e8eca296e070f8a72
Co-Authored-By: Anderson Mesquita <andersonvom@gmail.com>
"}]
commit_message:
Add `@ngInject` to Job route resolve function

During production builds, the minifier modifies variable names,
breaking Angular's automatic dependency injection. The ng-annotate
declaration `@ngInject` was missing from the `resolve` config
for the Job route, causing all `/job/*` paths to become
inaccessible. This adds the correct annotation to solve the issue.

Change-Id: Ic5f68c6f3dfc840b563bde0e8eca296e070f8a72
Co-Authored-By: Anderson Mesquita <andersonvom@gmail.com>

TrivialFix

commit_message:
Add unit tests to cover print_item_locations

Add unit tests to cover all code paths in print_item_locations
function in cli/info.py.

Update comment to match what's tested for invalid/missing policy.

Update tests to verify output of print_item_locations

Corrected PEP8 compliance violations.

Change-Id: I84958cb70205ee8d7ea246826dd56201fa642da9

commit_message:
Document the neutron-release team.

Gerrit includes a neutron-release team.  Document what this team means
today.  Also propose that this team have merge rights to *all* Neutron
git repos so that a small group has the ability to quickly unblock
things if needed, which is especially important around release time.

Change-Id: Id3d4d051278930841f64a4153e40a2dd3d893e44
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

Add tasks info to glance documentation

Do not use system config file for test

Use dummy config file so that test depends on default config opts
instead of system config file

Closes-Bug: #1511622

commit_message:
Fixes IPv6 Security Group rules with 128 prefix length

Hyper-V cannot add Extended ACLs which have /128 IPv6 IP addresses
in the RemoteIPAddress field.

Removes the /128 length from the remote_address field.

Change-Id: I9581740b7af58116e40cd094a813170b46de1623
Closes-Bug: #1505578
(cherry picked from commit 00773fc26e7bae9ac9440a530e37bd88b86a3791)

Hyper-V cannot add Extended ACLs which have /128 IPv6 IP addresses
in the RemoteIPAddress field.

Removes the /128 length from the remote_address field.

Closes-Bug: #1505578

[{'created': '2015-08-12 19:12:18.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] Simple navigation for details pages

Partial-Bug: 1413823
'}, {'created': '2015-09-23 14:13:09.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] Simple navigation for details pages

Adds a common detail page and a breadcrumb templatetag. The breadcrumb
templatetag defaults to displaying the panel name and the existing page
title, which is usually name_or_id. The templatetag can also access the
context, and accepts a "custom_breadcrumb", for complex nested pages or
customised layouts.

This style of navigation is also useful for small device
(mobile/tablet) style navigation, providing logical direction that isn't
dependant on the sidebar being displayed.

Currently implemented in Images, Volumes (simple breadcrumb), Ports and
Subnets (more complex nesting).

This approach has been chosen as manipulation of the URLs was seen as
undesirable, making request.path too unreliable. Furthermore, the
templatetag seperation means this could easily be used in other views.

Change-Id: I7443b2ffa61560e5d1fd4d6d91b11201f1db6fac
Partial-Bug: 1413823
